  <title>collision theory</title>
  <termversion>2.3.3</termversion>
  <lastupdated>2014-02-24</lastupdated>
  <definitions>
    <item>
      <id>1</id>
      <text>Various collision theories, dealing with the frequency of collision between reactant molecules, have been put forward. In the earliest theories reactant molecules were regarded as hard spheres, and a collision was considered to occur when the distance d between the centres of two molecules was equal to the sum of their radii. For a gas containing only one type of molecule, A, the collision density is given by simple collision theory as: Z AA = 2 π σ 2 u N A 2 2 is the number density of molecules and u is the mean molecular speed, given by kinetic theory to be 8kB.Tπm, where m is the molecular mass, and σ = π d AA 2. Thus: Z AA = 2 N A 2 σ 2 π k B T m for two unlike molecules A and B, of masses m A and m B is: Z AB = N A N B σ 2 π k B T µ is the reduced massm A m B m A + m B, and σ = π d AB 2. For the collision frequency factor these formulations lead to the following expression: z AA or z AB = L σ 2 8 π k B T µ is the Avogadro constant. More advanced collision theories, not involving the assumption that molecules behave as hard spheres, are known as generalized kinetic theories.</text>
